 213:     Compute the medial axis transform of a binary image
 214:     Parameters
 215:     ----------
 216:     image : binary ndarray, shape (M, N)
 217:         The image of the shape to be skeletonized.
 218:     mask : binary ndarray, shape (M, N), optional
 219:         If a mask is given, only those elements in `image` with a true
 220:         value in `mask` are used for computing the medial axis.
 221:     return_distance : bool, optional
 222:         If true, the distance transform is returned as well as the skeleton.
 223:     Returns
 224:     -------
 225:     out : ndarray of bools
 226:         Medial axis transform of the image
 227:     dist : ndarray of ints, optional
 228:         Distance transform of the image (only returned if `return_distance`
 229:         is True)
 230:     See also
 231:     --------
 232:     skeletonize
 233:     Notes
 234:     -----
 235:     This algorithm computes the medial axis transform of an image
 236:     as the ridges of its distance transform.
 237:     The different steps of the algorithm are as follows
 238:      * A lookup table is used, that assigns 0 or 1 to each configuration of
 239:        the 3x3 binary square, whether the central pixel should be removed
 240:        or kept. We want a point to be removed if it has more than one neighbor
 241:        and if removing it does not change the number of connected components.
 242:      * The distance transform to the background is computed, as well as
 243:        the cornerness of the pixel.
 244:      * The foreground (value of 1) points are ordered by
 245:        the distance transform, then the cornerness.
 246:      * A cython function is called to reduce the image to its skeleton. It
 247:        processes pixels in the order determined at the previous step, and
 248:        removes or maintains a pixel according to the lookup table. Because
 249:        of the ordering, it is possible to process all pixels in only one
 250:        pass.
 251:     Examples
 252:     --------
 253:     >>> square = np.zeros((7, 7), dtype=np.uint8)
 254:     >>> square[1:-1, 2:-2] = 1
 255:     >>> square
 256:     array([[0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0],
 257:            [0, 0, 1, 1, 1, 0, 0],
 258:            [0, 0, 1, 1, 1, 0, 0],
 259:            [0, 0, 1, 1, 1, 0, 0],
 260:            [0, 0, 1, 1, 1, 0, 0],
 261:            [0, 0, 1, 1, 1, 0, 0],
 262:            [0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0]], dtype=uint8)
 263:     >>> medial_axis(square).astype(np.uint8)
